er|2\n|align=center|3:23\n| \n|-\n|Featherweight 66&nbsp;kg\n|{{flagicon|RUS}} Temryuk Berkhamov\n|def.\n|{{flagicon|UKR}} Aleksandr Podlesniy    \n|Submission (Anaconda Choke)\n|align=center|2\n|align=center|2:28\n| \n|-\n|Featherweight 66&nbsp;kg\n|{{flagicon|RUS}} Maharbek Karginov\n|def.\n|{{flagicon|RUS}} Arsen Ubaidulaev       \n|Submission (Rear Naked Choke)\n|align=center|1\n|align=center|3:05\n| \n|-\n|Featherweight 66&nbsp;kg\n|{{flagicon|RUS}} Adlan Bataev\n|def.\n|{{flagicon|RUS}} Oleg Peterimov       \n|Decision (Unanimous)\n|align=center|3\n|align=center|5:00\n| \n|-\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n[[Category:Absolute Championship Akhmat]]\n[[Category:2015 in mixed martial arts]]\n[[Category:2015 in Russian sport|Absolute Championship Berkut events]]\n", "name_user": "Shadess", "label": "safe", "comment": "linkParviz AbdullayevusingFind link", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/2015_in_Absolute_Championship_Berkut"}
{"title_page": "Was mein Gott will, das g'scheh allzeit", "text_new": "{{Infobox musical composition\n| name                = {{lang|de|Was mein Gott will, das g'scheh allzeit|italic=no}}\n| type                = [[Lutheran hymn]]\n| composer            = \n| image               = Was mein Gott will, das gescheh allzeit (Edition Wackernagel).jpg\n| alt                 = \n| caption             = Edition of two early versions with commentary, [[Philipp Wackernagel]], 1870\n| translation         = \n| text                = attr. to [[Albert, Duke of Prussia]]\n| written             = c. 1550\n| language            = German\n| meter               = \n| melody              = [[Claudin de Sermisy]]\n| composed            = {{start date|1529}}\n| published           = {{start date|1647}}\n}}\n\"'''{{lang|de|Was mein Gott will, das g'scheh allzeit|italic=no}}'''\" (What my God wants, should always happen) is a [[Lutheran hymn]] in German. The text of c. 1550 is attributed to [[Albert, Duke of Prussia]].<ref name=\"hymnary\" /> The melody goes back to a tune by [[Claudin de Sermisy]], written in 1529 for a secular French song. The hymn has belonged to core Lutheran hymnody without interruption. It is part of the Protestant hymnal [[Evangelisches Gesangbuch]] as EG 364<!-- in the section ''Glaube \u2013 Liebe \u2013 Hoffnung. Angst und Vertrauen''-->.\n\nIt has been set to music throughout centuries, including by [[Johann Sebastian Bach]] who based a chorale cantata on it, [[Was mein Gott will, das g'scheh allzeit, BWV 111|''Was mein Gott will, das g'scheh allzeit'', BWV 111]], and used the first stanza as [[St Matthew Passion structure#31|a chorale in the ''St Matthew Passion'']]\n\n== Content and text ==\n\"{{lang|de|Was mein Gott will, das g'scheh allzeit|italic=no}}\" is an expression of unlimited trust in God, even when facing death.  The text as used in modern hymnals is:\n{{quote|<poem>\n1. Was mein Gott will, gescheh allzeit,\nsein Will, der ist der beste.\nZu helfen dem er ist bereit,\nder an ihn glaubet feste.\nEr hilft aus Not,\nder treue Gott,\ner tr\u00f6st' die Welt ohn Ma\u00dfen.\nWer Gott vertraut,\nfest auf ihn baut,\nden will er nicht verlassen.\n\n2. Gott ist mein Trost, mein Zuversicht,\nmein Hoffnung und mein Leben;\nwas mein Gott will, das mir geschicht,\nwill ich nicht widerstreben.\nSein Wort ist wahr,\ndenn all mein Haar\ner selber hat gez\u00e4hlet.\nEr h\u00fct' und wacht,\nstets f\u00fcr uns tracht'\nauf dass uns gar nichts fehlet.\n\n3. Drum, muss ich S\u00fcnder von der Welt\nhinfahrn nach Gottes Willen\nzu meinem Gott, wenn's ihm gef\u00e4llt,\nwill ich ihm halten stille.\nMein arme Seel\nich Gott befehl\nin meiner letzten Stunden:\ndu treuer Gott,\nS\u00fcnd, H\u00f6ll und Tod|\nhast du mir \u00fcberwunden.\n\n4. Noch eins, Herr, will ich bitten dich,\ndu wirst mir's nicht versagen:\nWenn mich der b\u00f6se Geist anficht,\nlass mich, Herr, nicht verzagen.\nHilf, steu'r und wehr,\nach Gott, mein Herr,\nzu Ehren deinem Namen.\nWer das begehrt,\ndem wird's gew\u00e4hrt.\nDrauf sprech ich fr\u00f6hlich: Amen.<ref name=\"hymnary\" /></poem>}}\n\nWhile hymnals such  the 1854 ''Kernlieder'' have \"und tr\u00f6stt die Welt mit Ma\u00dfen\" in the first stanza, about consolation of the world, other hymnals have \"und z\u00fcchtiget mit Ma\u00dfen\" (chastises in moderation), including ''[[Praxis Pietatis Melica]]'' in 1653, the {{ill|Deutsches Evangelisches Gesangbuch|de}} of 1914 und [[Otto Riethm\u00fcller]]'s ''Ein neues Lied'' of 1932. \n\n== Melody and musical settings ==\nThe hymn was sung from the beginning to a tune that originated with [[Claudin de Sermisy]], which was published in 1529 to a secular text, \"Il me suffit de tous mes maulx\".<ref name=\"Terry\" /><ref name=\"Winterfeld\" /> It appeared with a paraphrase of [[Psalm 129]] in 1540 in the [[Antwerp]] ''Souterliedekens'' (Psalm songs).<ref name=\"Terry\" /><ref name=\"BCW\" />\n\n[[File:BWV 244 Incipit Nr. 31 Was mein Gott will.svg|thumb|upright=1.6|Incipit in Bach's Passion]]\nThe artful original melody, with many [[Syncope (music)|syncopes]] and irregular metre was simplified early to notes of even length. [[Johann Sebastian Bach]] used this version in his chorale cantata [[Was mein Gott will, das g'scheh allzeit, BWV 111|''Was mein Gott will, das g'scheh allzeit'', BWV 111]]. He also used single stanzas in other cantatas, and the first stanza in his [[St Matthew Passion structure#31|St Matthew Passion]] as movement 31, as the reply of Jesus after his prayer in [[Gethsemane]].<ref name=\"Terry\" /><ref name=\"BCW\" /> In translations of the scene, it was rendered as \"O Father, let Thy will be done\".<ref name=\"Terry\" />\n\nComposers wrote settings for different scoring, for example [[Heinrich Sch\u00fctz]] in ''[[Geistliche Chormusik]]'' (No. 24), [[Georg Philipp Telemann]] in cantata TWV 1:1529, [[Max Reger]] in [[Reger works#135|Op. 135]]a No. 27, {{ill|Hermann Bendix|de}}, [[G\u00fcnter Raphael]] and {{ill|Erwin Amend|de}}.\n\n== References ==\n\n{{reflist\n| refs =\n\n<ref name=\"Terry\">{{cite book\n| last = Terry\n| first = Charles Sanford\n| authorlink = Charles Sanford Terry\n| url = https://oll.libertyfund.org/titles/bach-bachs-chorals-vol-1-the-hymns-and-hymn-melodies-of-the-passions-and-oratorios\n| title = No. 31.: O Father, let thy will be done (Was mein Gott will)\n| work = Johann Sebastian Bach, Bach\u2019s Chorals, vol. 1 The Hymns and Hymn Melodies of the \u201cPassions\u201d and Oratorios\n| publisher = oll.libertyfund.org\n| year = 1915\n}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"Winterfeld\">{{cite book\n| last = Winterfeld\n| first = Carl von\n| authorlink = \n| url = https://books.google.com/books?id=aOcsAAAAYAAJ&pg=PA71\n| title = Der evangelische Kirchengesang und sein Verh\u00e4ltni\u00df zur Kunst des Tonsatzes\n| location = [[Leipzig]]\n| publisher = oll.libertyfund.org\n| year = 1943\n| page = 71\n}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"BCW\">{{cite web\n| url = http://www.bach-cantatas.com/CM/Was-mein-Gott-will-das-gscheh-allzeit.htm\n| title = Chorale Melodies used in Bach's Vocal Works / Was mein Gott will, das g\u2019scheh allzeit\n| publisher = Bach Cantatas Website\n| year = 2009\n| accessdate = 5 April 2020\n}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"hymnary\">{{cite web\n| url = https://hymnary.org/text/was_mein_gott_will_das_gscheh_allzeit\n| title = mein Gott will, das g\u2019scheh allzeit\n| publisher = hymnary.org\n| accessdate = 5 April 2020\n}}</ref>\n<!--\n<ref name=\"Kelly\">{{cite web\n| url = http://www.hymnary.org/text/i_into_gods_own_heart_and_mind\n| title = I into God's own heart and mind\n| publisher = hymnary.org\n| accessdate = 11 February 2017\n}}</ref>-->\n\n}}\n\n== Literature ==\n* [[Philipp Wackernagel]]: ''1240. Was mein Gott will, das gescheh allzeit'' und ''1241. Was mein Gott will, das geschehe allzeit''. In: ''Das deutsche Kirchenlied von der \u00e4ltesten Zeit bis zu Anfang des XVII. Jahrhunderts'', 3. Band, Leipzig 1870, [https://reader.digitale-sammlungen.de/de/fs1/object/display/bsb11105578_01096.html pp. 1070-1071]\n\n== External links ==\n{{Commonscat|Was mein Gott will, das gscheh allzeit}}\n<!--* [http://gutenberg.spiegel.de/buch/-7513/94 Ich hab in Gottes Herz und Sinn] [[Der Spiegel]]-->\n* [http://www.bach-chorales.com/Scores/WasMeinGottWill_7SettingsAligned.pdf 7 J.S. Bach chorale settings of ''Was mein Gott will, das gscheh allzeit'', Zahn&nbsp;7568] by Luke Dahn (retrieved 21 June 2017)\n\n{{Lutheran hymns|state=collapsed}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n[[Category:1550s works]]\n[[Category:German Christian hymns]]\n[[Category:Lutheran hymns]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox musical composition\n| name                = {{lang|de|Was mein Gott will, das g'scheh allzeit|italic=no}}\n| type                = [[Lutheran hymn]]\n| composer            = \n| image               = Was mein Gott will, das gescheh allzeit (Edition Wackernagel).jpg\n| alt                 = \n| caption             = Edition of two early versions with commentary, [[Philipp Wackernagel]], 1870\n| translation         = \n| text                = attr. to [[Albert, Duke of Prussia]]\n| written             = c. 1550\n| language            = German\n| meter               = \n| melody              = [[Claudin de Sermisy]]\n| composed            = {{start date|1529}}\n| published           = {{start date|1647}}\n}}\n\"'''{{lang|de|Was mein Gott will, das g'scheh allzeit|italic=no}}'''\" (What my God wants, should always happen) is a [[Lutheran hymn]] in German. The text of c. 1550 is attributed to [[Albert, Duke of Prussia]].<ref name=\"hymnary\" /> The melody goes back to a tune by [[Claudin de Sermisy]], written in 1529 for a secular French song. The hymn has belonged to core Lutheran hymnody without interruption. It is part of the Protestant hymnal [[Evangelisches Gesangbuch]] as EG 364<!-- in the section ''Glaube \u2013 Liebe \u2013 Hoffnung. Angst und Vertrauen''-->.\n\nIt has been set to music throughout centuries, including by [[Johann Sebastian Bach]] who based a chorale cantata on it, [[Was mein Gott will, das g'scheh allzeit, BWV 111|''Was mein Gott will, das g'scheh allzeit'', BWV 111]], and used the first stanza as [[St Matthew Passion structure#31|a chorale in the ''St Matthew Passion'']]\n\n== Content and text ==\n\"{{lang|de|Was mein Gott will, das g'scheh allzeit|italic=no}}\" is an expression of unlimited trust in God, even when facing death.  The text as used in modern hymnals is:\n{{quote|<poem>\n1. Was mein Gott will, gescheh allzeit,\nsein Will, der ist der beste.\nZu helfen dem er ist bereit,\nder an ihn glaubet feste.\nEr hilft aus Not,\nder treue Gott,\ner tr\u00f6st' die Welt ohn Ma\u00dfen.\nWer Gott vertraut,\nfest auf ihn baut,\nden will er nicht verlassen.\n\n2. Gott ist mein Trost, mein Zuversicht,\nmein Hoffnung und mein Leben;\nwas mein Gott will, das mir geschicht,\nwill ich nicht widerstreben.\nSein Wort ist wahr,\ndenn all mein Haar\ner selber hat gez\u00e4hlet.\nEr h\u00fct' und wacht,\nstets f\u00fcr uns tracht'\nauf dass uns gar nichts fehlet.\n\n3. Drum, muss ich S\u00fcnder von der Welt\nhinfahrn nach Gottes Willen\nzu meinem Gott, wenn's ihm gef\u00e4llt,\nwill ich ihm halten stille.\nMein arme Seel\nich Gott befehl\nin meiner letzten Stunden:\ndu treuer Gott,\nS\u00fcnd, H\u00f6ll und Tod|\nhast du mir \u00fcberwunden.\n\n4. Noch eins, Herr, will ich bitten dich,\ndu wirst mir's nicht versagen:\nWenn mich der b\u00f6se Geist anficht,\nlass mich, Herr, nicht verzagen.\nHilf, steu'r und wehr,\nach Gott, mein Herr,\nzu Ehren deinem Namen.\nWer das begehrt,\ndem wird's gew\u00e4hrt.\nDrauf sprech ich fr\u00f6hlich: Amen.<ref name=\"hymnary\" /></poem>}}\n\nWhile hymnals such  the 1854 ''Kernlieder'' have \"und tr\u00f6stt die Welt mit Ma\u00dfen\" in the first stanza, about consolation of the world, other hymnals have \"und z\u00fcchtiget mit Ma\u00dfen\" (chastises in moderation), including ''[[Praxis Pietatis Melica]]'' in 1653, the {{ill|Deutsches Evangelisches Gesangbuch|de}} of 1914 und [[Otto Riethm\u00fcller]]'s ''Ein neues Lied'' of 1932. \n\n== Melody and musical settings ==\nThe hymn was sung from the beginning to a tune that originated with [[Claudin de Sermisy]], which was published in 1529 to a secular text, \"Il me suffit de tous mes maulx\".<ref name=\"Terry\" /><ref name=\"Winterfeld\" /> It appeared with a paraphrase of [[Psalm 129]] in 1540 in the [[Antwerp]] ''Souterliedekens'' (Psalm songs).<ref name=\"BCW\" />\n\n[[File:BWV 244 Incipit Nr. 31 Was mein Gott will.svg|thumb|upright=1.6|Incipit in Bach's Passion]]\nThe artful original melody, with many [[Syncope (music)|syncopes]] and irregular metre was simplified early to notes of even length. [[Johann Sebastian Bach]] used this version in his chorale cantata [[Was mein Gott will, das g'scheh allzeit, BWV 111|''Was mein Gott will, das g'scheh allzeit'', BWV 111]]. He also used single stanzas in other cantatas, and the first stanza in his [[St Matthew Passion structure#31|St Matthew Passion]] as movement 31, as the reply of Jesus after his prayer in [[Gethsemane]].<ref name=\"Terry\" /><ref name=\"BCW\" /> In translations of the scene, it was rendered as \"O Father, let Thy will be done\".<ref name=\"Terry\" />\n\nComposers wrote settings for different scoring, for example [[Heinrich Sch\u00fctz]] in ''[[Geistliche Chormusik]]'' (No. 24), [[Georg Philipp Telemann]] in cantata TWV 1:1529, [[Max Reger]] in [[Reger works#135|Op. 135]]a No. 27, {{ill|Hermann Bendix|de}}, [[G\u00fcnter Raphael]] and {{ill|Erwin Amend|de}}.\n\n== References ==\n\n{{reflist\n| refs =\n\n<ref name=\"Terry\">{{cite book\n| last = Terry\n| first = Charles Sanford\n| authorlink = Charles Sanford Terry\n| url = https://oll.libertyfund.org/titles/bach-bachs-chorals-vol-1-the-hymns-and-hymn-melodies-of-the-passions-and-oratorios\n| title = No. 31.: O Father, let thy will be done (Was mein Gott will)\n| work = Johann Sebastian Bach, Bach\u2019s Chorals, vol. 1 The Hymns and Hymn Melodies of the \u201cPassions\u201d and Oratorios\n| publisher = oll.libertyfund.org\n| year = 1915\n}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"Winterfeld\">{{cite book\n| last = Winterfeld\n| first = Carl von\n| authorlink = \n| url = https://books.google.com/books?id=aOcsAAAAYAAJ&pg=PA71\n| title = Der evangelische Kirchengesang und sein Verh\u00e4ltni\u00df zur Kunst des Tonsatzes\n| location = [[Leipzig]]\n| publisher = oll.libertyfund.org\n| year = 1943\n| page = 71\n}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"BCW\">{{cite web\n| url = http://www.bach-cantatas.com/CM/Was-mein-Gott-will-das-gscheh-allzeit.htm\n| title = Chorale Melodies used in Bach's Vocal Works / Was mein Gott will, das g\u2019scheh allzeit\n| publisher = Bach Cantatas Website\n| year = 2009\n| accessdate = 5 April 2020\n}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"hymnary\">{{cite web\n| url = https://hymnary.org/text/was_mein_gott_will_das_gscheh_allzeit\n| title = mein Gott will, das g\u2019scheh allzeit\n| publisher = hymnary.org\n| accessdate = 5 April 2020\n}}</ref>\n<!--\n<ref name=\"Kelly\">{{cite web\n| url = http://www.hymnary.org/text/i_into_gods_own_heart_and_mind\n| title = I into God's own heart and mind\n| publisher = hymnary.org\n| accessdate = 11 February 2017\n}}</ref>-->\n\n}}\n\n== Literature ==\n* [[Philipp Wackernagel]]: ''1240. Was mein Gott will, das gescheh allzeit'' und ''1241. Was mein Gott will, das geschehe allzeit''. In: ''Das deutsche Kirchenlied von der \u00e4ltesten Zeit bis zu Anfang des XVII. Jahrhunderts'', 3. Band, Leipzig 1870, [https://reader.digitale-sammlungen.de/de/fs1/object/display/bsb11105578_01096.html pp. 1070-1071]\n\n== External links ==\n{{Commonscat|Was mein Gott will, das gscheh allzeit}}\n<!--* [http://gutenberg.spiegel.de/buch/-7513/94 Ich hab in Gottes Herz und Sinn] [[Der Spiegel]]-->\n* [http://www.bach-chorales.com/Scores/WasMeinGottWill_7SettingsAligned.pdf 7 J.S. Bach chorale settings of ''Was mein Gott will, das gscheh allzeit'', Zahn&nbsp;7568] by Luke Dahn (retrieved 21 June 2017)\n\n{{Lutheran hymns|state=collapsed}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n[[Category:1550s works]]\n[[Category:German Christian hymns]]\n[[Category:Lutheran hymns]]\n", "name_user": "Gerda Arendt", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eMelody and musical settings:repeat ref", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Was_mein_Gott_will,_das_g%27scheh_allzeit"}
