{"title_page": "Con Sheehan", "text_new": "{{Infobox boxer\n| name = Cornelius Sheehan\n| image =\n| image_size =\n| caption =\n| nationality = [[Irish people|Irish]]\n| nickname = Con\n| height = 6 ft 5+1/2 in\n| reach =\n| weight = [[Heavyweight]]\n| birth_date = {{Birth date and age|1989|3|3|df=y}}\n| birth_place = [[Clonmel]], [[County Tipperary|Tipperary]], [[Republic of Ireland|Ireland]]\n| style = [[Orthodox stance|Orthodox]]\n| total = 6\n| wins = 6\n| KO = 1\n| losses = 0\n| draws = 0\n| no contests = 0\n| show-medals    = yes\n| medaltemplates = \n{{MedalCountry| {{IRL}} }}\n{{MedalCompetition|[[European Union Amateur Boxing Championships|European Union Amateur Championships]]}}\n{{MedalSilver| [[2008 European Union Amateur Boxing Championships|2008 Cetniewo]] |[[Heavyweight]]}}\n{{MedalGold| [[2009 European Union Amateur Boxing Championships|2009 Odense]] |[[Heavyweight]]}}\n}}\n\n'''Cornelius \"Con\" Sheehan''' (born 3 March 1989) is an Irish boxer from [[Clonmel]], [[Republic of Ireland|Ireland]]. As an amateur the became the youngest ever Irish Elite Heavyweight champion winning a total of a six [[Irish Athletic Boxing Association|Irish]] Elite titles, four at heavyweight and two at super heavyweight. He also represented The Leipzig Leopards in the [[World Series of Boxing]] and won a gold and a silver medal in two consecutive years at the [[European Union Amateur Boxing Championships]]. Since turning professional he is undefeated in six contests.<ref name=\"TippLive\">{{Cite web|title = Amateur boxing champion Con Sheehan to turn professional|url = https://www.tipperarylive.ie/news/sport/197586/Amateur-boxing-champion-Con-Sheehan-to.html|website = Tipperary Live = 2015-01-16}}</ref><ref>[http://sportsnewsireland.com/boxing/boxing_irish/boxing-news-con-sheehan-leaves-iaba-to-turn-pro Con Sheehan amateur boxing record]. SportsNewsIreland.com. Retrieved on 20 Jan 2016.</ref>\n\n==Amateur career==\nSheehan boxed for Clonmel Boxing Club, where he was trained by Martin Fennessy. He debuted as a Senior boxer in the Heavyweight division before later moving to Super Heavyweight. His first [[Irish Amateur Boxing Association|Irish Elite title]] came in 2008 at Heavyweight with a points victory over Tommy Sheehan in the final. Sheehan would go on to six Irish Elite titles.<ref name=\"Phil Boxing\">{{Cite web|title = Irish eyes are smilin' Manager Gary Hyde signs Irish heavyweight prospect Con Sheehan|url = http://philboxing.com/news/story-104106.html|website = Phil Boxing = 2016-06-10}}</ref>\n\nIn the [[2008 European Union Amateur Boxing Championships]] in Cetniewo, Poland, competed at Heavyweight earning victories over [[Stephen Simmons (boxer)|Stephen Simmons]] from Scotland (15:6) in the Quarter Finals and Germany's Vahagn Sahakyan (10:7) in the semis.  In the final he faced the favoured Greek boxer [[Helias Pavlidis]], against whom he lost on points (12:29) earning a silver medal.<ref name=\"BBC Chicago\">{{Cite web|title = GB boxers guaranteed five medals at European Champs|url = http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/boxing/8731504.stm|website = BBC News = 2010-06-09}}</ref><ref name=\"Strefa EU2008\">{{Cite web|title = 6.European Union Championships - Cetniewo, Poland - June 16-21 2008|url = http://amateur-boxing.strefa.pl/Championships/EuropeanUnion2008.html|website = Strefa = 2016-06-10}}</ref>\n\nThe following year [[2008 European Union Amateur Boxing Championships|European Union Championships]] took place in Odense, Denmark, and Sheehan competed again in the Heavyweight division. In the semi finals he beat England's [[Warren Baister]] in the Semi Finals and beat Spain's Juan Oliva Aleman (13:2) in the finals to earn a gold medal.<ref name=\"Strefa EU2008\">{{Cite web|title = 6.European Union Championships - Cetniewo, Poland - June 16-21 2008|url = http://amateur-boxing.strefa.pl/Championships/EuropeanUnion2008.html|website = Strefa = 2016-06-10}}</ref>\n\nIn his last national elite championships, Sheehan earned a points victories over Jason Barrons, Niall Kennedy and clubmate Dean Gardiner to clinch the 2014 Irish Super Heavyweight title.\n\n==Professional career==\nIn 2015, Sheehan moved to the USA to train under Virgil Hunter at King\u2019s Boxing Gym in [[Oakland, California]]. Sheehan made his professional debut on January 19, 2016 against Jonathan Rice in [[Club Nokia]], [[Los Angeles]], [[California]], [[United States]].\n\n==Professional boxing record==\n{{S-start}}\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" colspan=\"8\"|'''6 Wins''' (1 Knockouts), '''0 Losses''', '''0 Draw'''<ref name=\"record\">[http://boxrec.com/boxer/743155 Con Sheehan's Professional Boxing Record]. BoxRec.com. Retrieved on 20 Jan 2016.</ref>\n|-  style=\"text-align:center; background:#e3e3e3;\"\n|  style=\"border-style:none none solid solid; \"|'''Res.'''\n|  style=\"border-style:none none solid solid; \"|'''Record'''\n|  style=\"border-style:none none solid solid; \"|'''Opponent'''\n|  style=\"border-style:none none solid solid; \"|'''Type'''\n|  style=\"border-style:none none solid solid; \"|'''Rd., Time'''\n|  style=\"border-style:none none solid solid; \"|'''Date'''\n|  style=\"border-style:none none solid solid; \"|'''Location'''\n|  style=\"border-style:none none solid solid; \"|'''Notes'''\n|- align=center\n|{{yes2}}Win\n|6\u20130\n|align=left|{{Flag icon|CZE}} Tomas Mrazek\n|{{small|PTS}}\n|8\n|June 24, 2017\n|align=left|{{small|{{Flag icon|UK}} Wythenshawe Forum, [[Manchester]], [[England]]}}\n|\n|- align=center\n|{{yes2}}Win\n|5\u20130\n|align=left|{{Flag icon|HUN}} Ferenc Zsalek\n|{{small|PTS}}\n|8\n|Mar 10, 2017\n|align=left|{{small|{{Flag icon|UK}} [[Waterfront Hall]], [[Belfast]], [[Northern Ireland]]}}\n|\n|- align=center\n|{{yes2}}Win\n|4\u20130\n|align=left|{{Flag icon|POL}} Kamil Sokolowski\n|{{small|PTS}}\n|8\n|Nov 5, 2016\n|align=left|{{small|{{Flag icon|UK}} [[Titanic Belfast|Titanic Exhibition Centre]], [[Belfast]], [[Northern Ireland]]}}\n|\n|- align=center\n|{{yes2}}Win\n|3\u20130\n|align=left|{{Flag icon|Czech Republic}} Radek Varak\n|{{small|TKO}}\n|1 (8), {{small|1:32}}\n|Oct 1, 2016\n|align=left|{{small|{{Flag icon|UK}} [[Old Trafford Cricket Ground|Old Trafford]], [[Manchester]], [[England]]}}\n|\n|- align=center\n|{{yes2}}Win\n|2\u20130\n|align=left|{{Flag icon|Croatia}} Igor Mihaljevic\n|{{small|PTS}}\n|4\n|Sep 24, 2016\n|align=left|{{small|{{Flag icon|UK}} Tudor Grange Leisure Centre, [[Solihull]], [[West Midlands (region)|West Midlands]], [[England]]}}\n|\n|- align=center\n|{{yes2}}Win\n|1\u20130\n|align=left|{{Flag icon|USA}} Jonathan Rice\n|{{small|UD}}\n|4\n|Jan 19, 2016\n|align=left|{{small|{{Flag icon|USA}} [[Club Nokia]], [[Los Angeles]], [[California]], [[United States]]}}\n|align=left|{{small|Professional debut.}}\n{{S-end}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{boxrec|id=743155}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Sheehan, Con}}\n[[Category:1989 births]]\n[[Category:Heavyweight boxers]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:People from County Tipperary]]\n[[Category:People from Clonmel]]\n[[Category:Irish male boxers]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox boxer\n| name = Cornelius Sheehan\n| image =\n| image_size =\n| caption =\n| nationality = [[Irish people|Irish]]\n| nickname = Con\n| height = 6 ft 5+1/2 in\n| reach =\n| weight = [[Heavyweight]]\n| birth_date = {{Birth date and age|1989|3|3|df=y}}\n| birth_place = [[Clonmel]], [[County Tipperary|Tipperary]], [[Republic of Ireland|Ireland]]\n| style = [[Orthodox stance|Orthodox]]\n| total = 6\n| wins = 6\n| KO = 1\n| losses = 0\n| draws = 0\n| no contests = 0\n| show-medals    = yes\n| medaltemplates = \n{{MedalCountry| {{IRL}} }}\n{{MedalCompetition|[[European Union Amateur Boxing Championships|European Union Amateur Championships]]}}\n{{MedalSilver| [[2008 European Union Amateur Boxing Championships|2008 Cetniewo]] |[[Heavyweight]]}}\n{{MedalGold| [[2009 European Union Amateur Boxing Championships|2009 Odense]] |[[Heavyweight]]}}\n}}\n\n'''Cornelius \"Con\" Sheehan''' (born 3 March 1989) is an Irish boxer from [[Clonmel]], [[Republic of Ireland|Ireland]]. As an amateur the became the youngest ever Irish Elite Heavyweight champion winning a total of a six [[IABA|Irish]] Elite titles, four at heavyweight and two at super heavyweight. He also represented The Leipzig Leopards in the [[World Series of Boxing]] and won a gold and a silver medal in two consecutive years at the [[European Union Amateur Boxing Championships]]. Since turning professional he is undefeated in six contests.<ref name=\"TippLive\">{{Cite web|title = Amateur boxing champion Con Sheehan to turn professional|url = https://www.tipperarylive.ie/news/sport/197586/Amateur-boxing-champion-Con-Sheehan-to.html|website = Tipperary Live = 2015-01-16}}</ref><ref>[http://sportsnewsireland.com/boxing/boxing_irish/boxing-news-con-sheehan-leaves-iaba-to-turn-pro Con Sheehan amateur boxing record]. SportsNewsIreland.com. Retrieved on 20 Jan 2016.</ref>\n\n==Amateur career==\nSheehan boxed for Clonmel Boxing Club, where he was trained by Martin Fennessy. He debuted as a Senior boxer in the Heavyweight division before later moving to Super Heavyweight. His first [[Irish Amateur Boxing Association|Irish Elite title]] came in 2008 at Heavyweight with a points victory over Tommy Sheehan in the final. Sheehan would go on to six Irish Elite titles.<ref name=\"Phil Boxing\">{{Cite web|title = Irish eyes are smilin' Manager Gary Hyde signs Irish heavyweight prospect Con Sheehan|url = http://philboxing.com/news/story-104106.html|website = Phil Boxing = 2016-06-10}}</ref>\n\nIn the [[2008 European Union Amateur Boxing Championships]] in Cetniewo, Poland, competed at Heavyweight earning victories over [[Stephen Simmons]] from Scotland (15:6) in the Quarter Finals and Germany's Vahagn Sahakyan (10:7) in the semis.  In the final he faced the favoured Greek boxer [[Helias Pavlidis]], against whom he lost on points (12:29) earning a silver medal.<ref name=\"BBC Chicago\">{{Cite web|title = GB boxers guaranteed five medals at European Champs|url = http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/boxing/8731504.stm|website = BBC News = 2010-06-09}}</ref><ref name=\"Strefa EU2008\">{{Cite web|title = 6.European Union Championships - Cetniewo, Poland - June 16-21 2008|url = http://amateur-boxing.strefa.pl/Championships/EuropeanUnion2008.html|website = Strefa = 2016-06-10}}</ref>\n\nThe following year [[2008 European Union Amateur Boxing Championships|European Union Championships]] took place in Odense, Denmark, and Sheehan competed again in the Heavyweight division. In the semi finals he beat England's [[Warren Baister]] in the Semi Finals and beat Spain's Juan Oliva Aleman (13:2) in the finals to earn a gold medal.<ref name=\"Strefa EU2008\">{{Cite web|title = 6.European Union Championships - Cetniewo, Poland - June 16-21 2008|url = http://amateur-boxing.strefa.pl/Championships/EuropeanUnion2008.html|website = Strefa = 2016-06-10}}</ref>\n\nIn his last national elite championships, Sheehan earned a points victories over Jason Barrons, Niall Kennedy and clubmate Dean Gardiner to clinch the 2014 Irish Super Heavyweight title.\n\n==Professional career==\nIn 2015, Sheehan moved to the USA to train under Virgil Hunter at King\u2019s Boxing Gym in [[Oakland, California]]. Sheehan made his professional debut on January 19, 2016 against Jonathan Rice in [[Club Nokia]], [[Los Angeles]], [[California]], [[United States]].\n\n==Professional boxing record==\n{{S-start}}\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" colspan=\"8\"|'''6 Wins''' (1 Knockouts), '''0 Losses''', '''0 Draw'''<ref name=\"record\">[http://boxrec.com/boxer/743155 Con Sheehan's Professional Boxing Record]. BoxRec.com. Retrieved on 20 Jan 2016.</ref>\n|-  style=\"text-align:center; background:#e3e3e3;\"\n|  style=\"border-style:none none solid solid; \"|'''Res.'''\n|  style=\"border-style:none none solid solid; \"|'''Record'''\n|  style=\"border-style:none none solid solid; \"|'''Opponent'''\n|  style=\"border-style:none none solid solid;